New and sensitive devices that are based on monitoring changes in intensity in one or more light beams or changes in their phases when interacting with physical systems are known as optical sensors [68]. Benefits such as sensitivity, time-saving, and selectivity have led to the selection of optical sensors for the detection of various AAs [92,93]. Metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) have been considered as a porous crystalline material with applications such as chemical assay, drug delivery, biological imaging, adsorption and separation in recent years. In 2019, Yang and colleagues [94], designed an signal OFF-ON fluorescence sensor to detect l-Cys in biological fluids using this material (CaII-MOFs (((Ca1.5(8-HL1)(DMF)2)DMF)n). Pb2+ as quencher was used to switch the state and the fluorescence signal was gradually regained when l-Cys was introduced to the structure of CaII-MOFs/Pb2+ in the following stage. The linear range of this technique was 0.05 to 40 μM, with a LOD of 15 nM. Finally, l-Cys has also been detected in human serum samples using this method (Fig. 2
                              ). Their architecture with good water dispersion, good fluorescence, and light stability can be a better initiative. The use of new materials that have not been used much before creates a special attraction. In another similar report, Liu et al., 
                              [95], developed a fluorescence probe to highly sensitive detection of Cys. In this report, fluorescence intensity of nitrogen-doped GQDs (N-GQDs) was suppressed by Hg (II) ion. Fluorescence spectra have been regained after the addition of Cys to create a combination with Hg (II) ion. The linear range of this system was 0.05–30 μM, with a LOD of 1.3 nM. This method is known as innovative work. The use of GQDs with excellent optical and electrical features can also be seen in this work.

The results of the studies related to sensing and biosensing of Met are summarized in Table 2
                              . Some of nanomaterials (CuO NFs, Si NPs and MoS2) have been used in a few studies. However, nanomaterials are effective in amplifying the signal and achieving a better response. Therefore, the use of metal, carbon-based, polymeric and silicate NPs are recommended in the development of Met diagnostic sensors. On the other hand, the importance of measurement techniques that are based on bio-receptors is also interesting, which has received less attention. Table 2 reveals that fluorescence and EC based sensors have attracted the most attention, but these methods need for more work to be used in reliable manner. Among the analytical data of all types of sensors, PEC method data is superior. Overall, the reported studies for EC, fluorescence and PEC sensors had detection ranges of 0.001 to 1.39 μM, 0.0284 to 1.4 μM and 0.00003 μM, respectively. Literature review shows that there is no use of ECL, optical (SPR and FRET) and piezoelectric methods. Additionally, only one report was found for PEC. Also, there is no report for the biosensing of l-Met using bioreceptors like aptamer, DNA, enzyme and monoclonal antibodies. So, biotechnologist suggested to work in this research area toward preparation of novel aptamer for the specific monitoring of Met in real samples. Finally, it is predicted that accessible and portable sensors will be created for low-cost, fast and sensitive on-site detection of Met so that every-one can check their health condition using simple personalized medicine (see Table 3
                              ).

In another example, Cao and coworkers [167] created a ternary system with an anionic surfactant, cationic fluorophore, and Cu2+ as a selective and Arg-sensitive sensor. For further explanation, the combination of cationic derivatives of dansyl (DIlSD) with anionic surfactant (SDS assemblies) increased the fluorescence intensity and maximum wavelength, which was determined by color change. The fluorescence was switched off in the presence of Cu2+. The efficiency of fluorescence quenching has been greatly increased through Arg titration (Fig. 4
                              ). Under optimum conditions, the LOD was equal to 0.17 μM. Also, Zeng et al., 
                              [168] suggested to use water-soluble carbon dots (CDs) for the sensitive determination of Arg in real samples. CDs has a blue fluorescence with a quantum efficiency of 40 % and has good solubility in water. After adding Arg enantiomers (L and D) to the CDs solution, the fluorescence intensity increased. The above system recorded the LOD of 28.5 nM in the concentration range of 3 to 124 μM. This probe recorded the same data for both enantiomers of Arg. In the engineered approach, it could identify the target in human urine samples.

Wang et al. 
                           [276] designed an ECL-based sensor to determine d-Ala using the unique properties of functionalized (F)-MWCNTs and Au-Pt. DAAO was used to determine the specificity of d-Ala. Finally, GCE was modified with DAAO/Au–PtNPs/F-MWCNTs (Fig. 8
                           ) and exhibited a linear range of 5 nM to 5 mM and a LOD of 1.7 nM. As it is clear from the above research, the intelligent combination of NPs with excellent properties and the existence of DAAO for the selective performance of this sensor is a suitable approach to target Ala analyte.
